item.title: Who is Victor?
item.dc:creator: victor
item.content:encoded:
Hello, I'm Victor Sobrado.

Attentive and detail-oriented Systems Engineer with 7+ years of experience installing, configuring and maintaining enterprise networks and cloud infrastructure standards.

My Expertise

Systems and Network Engineering Technical Infrastructure (LAN/WAN/VPN/AWS) Open-source Tools & Technical Documentation End-to-End Tactical Troubleshooting System Backup, Security and Recovery Telecommunications (VoIP/ISDN/SIP)

My Experience

Network Engineer at NewCloud Networks

February 2018 – 

Troubleshooting, implementing, maintaining and scaling LAN/WAN/VPN/Virtual environments. Monitoring system availability, trends, and resources using Solarwinds/Nagios/Etc. Recording accurate and detailed notes for the knowledgebase and ticketing system. Routinely monitoring a HIPAA, PCI-DSS, and SSAE/SOC 2 compliant data center.

Network Operations Technician at NetCarrier

2014 – 2017

Monitored company and customer circuits, core and edge devices. Leveraged, interpreted and maintained internal monitoring systems. Served as a tier-II escalation point for telecommunications, Linux systems and networking issues. Maintained DNS, SWIP, databases and IP registrations for a nationwide carrier network. Managed shared web servers, virtual hosted PBX servers and SSL certificates. Assisted in colocation management and as a backup for emergency dispatch.

Sales Representative at We R Wireless

2013 – 2014

Met monthly and weekly sales goals on a regular basis. Researched and proposed potential sales opportunities to customers and management. Developed a network of customers, colleagues and small/medium businesses. Opened and maintained individual, family, and business accounts. Qualified customers for wireless, fiber, security and home telephony solutions.

Senior Resident Technician at Staples

2010 - 2013
Provided OS and hardware support, diagnostics, repair and consultation services to the public in-store. Traveled to customer locations to install home networking equipment and provide on-site support. Attended quarterly product and service announcements and vendor training webinars. Earned employee of the month on several occasions as well as written recognition for exceeding corporate sales metrics in our region.

My Education

Penn State University Bachelor of Science in Information Sciences and Technology, 2020 3.84 GPA Lansdale School of Business Associate of Specialized Business in Technology, 2014 Network Administration

My Certifications

Cisco CCENT 80% Cisco CCNA 50% AWS Certified SysOps Administrator 80% Comptia Network+ 99%, vouchered Still interested? Shoot me an email hello@victorsobrado.com.

item.title: The fight for #BroadbandPrivacy isn't over
item.dc:creator: victor
item.content:encoded: [caption id="attachment_88" align="alignleft" width="266"] Source: https://www.fcc.gov/reports-research/reports/measuring-broadband-america/measuring-broadband-america-2015[/caption] In (late) October of last year, the FCC announced a new set of privacy rules that enhanced the privacy and security of broadband consumers and telecommunications carriers. The rules limited the power broadband providers had to collect and use consumer data and put the decision back into the hands of consumers. The rules were crafted to give consumers a choice by requiring that consumers "Opt-in" and agree to share their data with broadband providers and third parties. The rules also set transparency requirements which would've required broadband providers to clearly state what information was being collected and how it was to be used. The specific data being collected can vary from sales, user financial data and browsing history. Unfortunately for broadband consumers, the FCC Broadband Privacy rules did not fare well in congress, losing by a 50-48 vote. With the media covering the highly controversial American Health Care Act and the attack in London,  the privacy rules did not receive the attention they deserved. The FCC has been very quiet about the vote on broadband privacy lately and with the exception of a few in congress and action committees, the efforts were seemingly too little/too late. With lavish contributions, ISP lobbyists were able to push this vote right by in around 10 hours. The Broadband Privacy rules were drafted after large ISPs such were found to be modifying HTTP packets to track users and other providers were exploring options to force users to pay additional fees for privacy. Without these rules, ISPs consumers have zero control over their online privacy. ISPs will have the direct ability to sell consumer browsing data to advertisers for an added layer of targeted advertising. [caption id="attachment_56" align="alignleft" width="300"] Source:http://www.socialmediaexaminer.com/optimize-your-facebook-ads/[/caption] With much of the internet turning into a commercial advertising cesspool, fitted with enough clickbait articles to thoughtlessly waste hours upon hours of our limited lives, it seems there is little escape from the advertisements. Often times these advertisements are simply not appropriately placed and are very intrusive (I'm looking at you, full screen advertisements).  These days many consumers do not understand online "fingerprinting" and what methods are used by advertising giants to create concise profiles of us on the web. Many experts are even blissfully unaware of what information is out there. Overall, ISPs have won a huge victory and broadband privacy has once again paid the price. American broadband privacy and advertising puts us eons behind that of Europe. Let's chalk this up as a minor setback with the understanding that we must continue to fight for online privacy. Net Neutrality will be the next target.

item.title: Voicemail MongoDB query for OpenUC 16.04+ Mailbox report
item.dc:creator: vsobrado
item.content:encoded:
Once upon a time, the best way to check on the number of stored voicemails was by using the Java tool:
 java -jar /usr/share/java/sipXecs/sipXivr/gridfs-voicemail-cli.jar --queryMailbox 303
As of version 16.04 which comes with an upgraded version of MongoDB, we can simply run this query instead of checking individual mailboxes with a bash script. 
db.fs.files.aggregate([
    {"$group":
        {_id:"$metadata.user", 
             "Inbox":{
                    "$sum":{
                        "$cond":{if :{"$eq":["$metadata.folder", "inbox"]}, then: 1, else: 0}
                         }
                   },
             "Saved":{
                    "$sum":{
                        "$cond":{if :{"$eq":["$metadata.folder", "saved"]}, then: 1, else: 0}
                         }
                    },
             "Conference":{
                    "$sum":{
                        "$cond":{if :{"$eq":["$metadata.folder", "conference"]}, then: 1, else: 0}
                         }
                   },
             "Deleted":{
                    "$sum":{
                        "$cond":{if :{"$eq":["$metadata.folder", "deleted"]}, then: 1, else: 0}
                         }
                   }
            }
    }
    ])
Which, should give you something like this: 

...
    {
      "_id": "137",
      "Inbox": 3,

      "Saved": 1,
      "Conference": 0,
      "Deleted": 3
    },
    {
      "_id": "145",
      "Inbox": 0,
      "Saved": 1,
      "Conference": 0,
      "Deleted": 12
    }
...

item.title: Community Gardening
item.dc:creator: vsobrado
item.content:encoded:
Earlier this season, we've decided to give a shot at gardening. Having only grown tomatoes and peppers on the east coast in containers, this was a relaxing and enjoyable way to have plenty of fresh vegetables. In particular, we're going to have enough pickles to last for quite some time.

There have been plenty lessons learned such as the proper spacing for tomatoes and dealing with common pests like the Japanese Beetle and small Rabbits. Next year we're going to rent an additional plot in the community garden and shoot for more Zucchini.
